Sure! Here's a code snippet in JavaScript that creates a simple todo list application using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Todo List App</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Todo List</h1>
        <input type="text" id="todoInput" placeholder="Enter todo...">
        <button onclick="addTodo()">Add</button>
        <ul id="todoList"></ul>
    </div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (styles.css):
```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    text-align: center;
}

.container {
    max-width: 400px;
    margin: 0 auto;
}

ul {
    list-style-type: none;
    padding: 0;
}

li {
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    padding: 5px;
    background-color: #f7f7f7;
}
```

JavaScript (script.js):
```javascript
function addTodo() {
    const todoInput = document.getElementById('todoInput').value;
    if (todoInput !== '') {
        const todoList = document.getElementById('todoList');
        const newTodo = document.createElement('li');
        newTodo.textContent = todoInput;
        todoList.appendChild(newTodo);
        document.getElementById('todoInput').value = '';
    } else {
        alert('Please enter a todo.');
    }
}
```

This code will create a simple todo list application where users can enter todos and add them to the list. The todos will be displayed as list items in an unordered list.
